ce:section.ce:para:
The formation of carbon quantum dots was investigated utilizing UV–visible spectroscopy. The UV–visible spectrum of the aqueous dispersion of carbon quantum dots derived from pomegranate peel is illustrated in Fig. 2
                        . Two dominant UV–vis absorption peaks displaying at around 220, 280 nm, that can be related to π-π∗ shift of C=C bonds. While, a shoulder at 320 nm is assigned to the n- π∗ shift of C=O bonds or other connected groups in CQDs [28,52]. The X-ray diffraction (XRD) pattern (Fig. 3
                        ) displayed a lot of noise at baseline and a wide diffraction peak at 2θ = 21.89 clearing the amorphous structure of the CQDs. The same result reported by Ref. [53]. The FTIR spectrum showed some frequent feature absorption peaks at around 3236–3552 cm−1 (CH2, OH, NH stretching vibration) covering each other and 1712 cm−1 (C=O stretching vibration) (Fig. 4
                        ). The same results have been reported in other experiments. A slight but sharp peak at, 1615 cm−1 could be to the C-O bonds [53,54].
